#Text=Gloucester Courthouse
#Text=Gloucester is a small town in the Hampton Roads region of Eastern Virginia .
#Text=Gloucester is located on Virginia 's Middle Peninsula , directly across the York River from York County .
#Text=Gloucester was founded in 1651 from the original York River Shire .
#Text=Gloucester is the site of Werowocomoco , the chief city of the Powhatan tribe prior to the arrival of the English .
#Text=It is a mostly rural county , with large tracts of farmland and a large population of watermen .
#Text=Its close proximity to the Historic Triangle of Jamestown , Williamsburg , and Yorktown have shaped its history .
#Text=By car

#Text=From the Virginia Peninsula ( Yorktown , Newport News , Hampton ) and points south , visitors enter Gloucester from US-17 across the George P. Coleman Memorial Bridge , spanning the York River .
#Text=From the Peninsula , US-17 can be easily accessed from Interstate 64 .
#Text=From Richmond and points West , the easiest way into Gloucester via Interstate 64 is through the town of West Point on State Route 33 .
#Text=SR-33 crosses US-17 at Glenns in the northern part of Gloucester County .
#Text=Traveling on US-17 South will direct you to the Courthouse and Gloucester Point area .
#Text=From the North , one can take I-95 South to I-64 and travel through West Point through Gloucester .
#Text=Alternatively , US-17 spans from Gloucester to Warrenton , Fredericksburg , and Tappahanock and provides a leisurely , four-lane drive to Gloucester .
#Text=SR-3 may also be used to get to Gloucester via Fredericksburg , offering scenic views of the Piankatank River along the way .
#Text=By plane

#Text=Gloucester is located approximately 20 minutes from Newport News-Williamsburg International Airport , approximately 60 minutes from Norfolk International Airport , and approximately 90 minutes from Richmond International Airport .
#Text=Get around
#Text=There is no public transportation system in Gloucester County .
#Text=Vehicle transportation is recommended .
#Text=The majority of businesses and tourist attractions are located on or near US-17 , the main artery through the county .
#Text=See
#Text=Rosewell ( Gloucester Point ) .
#Text=Monday - Saturday , 10AM-4PM , and Sunday 1PM-4PM .
#Text=The ancestral home of the Page family .
#Text=The house was destroyed by fire in 1916 , but the APVA maintains the ruins and an accompanying visitor center .
#Text=The College of William and Mary 's Virginia Institute of Marine Science ( VIMS ) , located in Gloucester Point , offers public tours by appointment .
#Text=The tour includes a visit to the Visitor 's Center and Aquarium , a VIMS Research Laboratory , and the VIMS Teaching Marsh .
#Text=Allow 1.5 hours .
#Text=Tours may be reserved by calling VIMS at +1 804 684-7846.
#Text=The historic Gloucester Courthouse area ( accessed via Main Street ) includes the historic Courthouse .
#Text=Located nearby is the Gloucester Museum of History .
#Text=The museum is open Monday through Friday , 10AM - 3PM and Saturdays 11AM - 4PM .
#Text=The Point Walk , 1255 Greate Rd ( Gloucester Point Beach ) .
#Text=Offers an interpretive walk along the York River .
#Text=Do
#Text=In the summer months , public beach access is available at Gloucester Point .
#Text=Beaverdam Park , located at 8687 Roaring Springs Road , is a 1340-acre park surrounding a 635-acre lake .
#Text=The park offers numerous hiking trails , and fishing and canoeing are popular activities in the lake .
#Text=The annual Daffodil Festival occurs in late March/early April .
#Text=The festival celebrates Gloucester 's status as a large cultivator of the Daffodil Flower .
#Text=Festivities occur on Main Street in the Gloucester Courthouse area and include food , children 's activities , art displays , craft vendors and Daffodil-related exhibits .
#Text=The annual Guinea Jubilee occurs in late September .
#Text=The festival celebrates the Guinea area of Gloucester County , home to a large population of watermen .
#Text=The festival is held each year at the Abingdon Ruritan Club off of Guinea Road .
#Text=The Jubilee showcases the fine seafood of the Guinea area .
#Text=Buy
#Text=The Gloucester Courthouse area , accessible off of US-17 via US-17 Business ( Main Street ) is home to numerous shops and restaurants .
#Text=Eat
#Text=Nick 's Spaghetti and Steakhouse , 1440 George Washington Memorial Highway ( US-17 ) , ☏ +1804 642-2330 .
#Text=Nick 's serves Italian cuisine and steak in a casual environment .
#Text=Sweet Madeline 's , 2091 George Wasthington Memorial Highway ( US-17 ) , ☏ +1804 642-1780 .
#Text=Sweet Madeline 's is a gourmet deli and bakery serving lunch .
#Text=Goodfellas , 5036 George Washington Memorial Highway ( US-17 ) , ☏ +1804 693-5950 .
#Text=Goodfellas specializes in Prime Rib , Seafood and Pasta .
#Text=Sal 's Sicilian Pizza and Restaurant , 2520 George Washington Memorial Highway , ☏ +1804 642-6470 .
#Text=Sal 's is a traditional Sicilian pizzaria .
#Text=Short Lane Ice Cream Company , 6721 George Washington Memorial Highway , ☏ +1804 695-2999 .
#Text=Serves hand-made ice cream in a restored general store .
#Text=In addition , fast food restaurants operate at Gloucester Point and Gloucester Courthouse .
#Text=An Applebee 's and Ruby Tuesday 's operate near Gloucester Courthouse .
#Text=Drink
#Text=There are a few sports bars in Gloucester , but no dance clubs or nightclubs .
#Text=However , many of the full-service restaurants offer bar service .
#Text=Sleep
#Text=The North River Inn , ☏ +1804 693-1616 , toll-free : +1 877-248-3030 .
#Text=Comfort Inn - Gloucester , 6639 Forest Hill Ave ( near the Courthouse area off of US-17 ) , ☏ +1804 695-1900 .
#Text=Hampton Inn - Gloucester , 6638 Forest Hill Ave ( near the Courthouse area off of US-17 ) , ☏ +1804 693-9393 .
#Text=Thousand Trails Campground - Chesapeake Bay , 12014 Trails Ln ( in the northern end of Gloucester County ) , ☏ +1804 693-6924 .
#Text=Thousand Trails offers campground sites for RVs and cabin rentals in a quiet setting .
#Text=Numerous water activities abound .
#Text=Go next
#Text=Yorktown , site of the final major battle of the American Revolutionary War , is located across the York River from Gloucester .
#Text=The National Park Service maintains a visitor center ( admission required ) and tours of battlefields and historic sites associated with the Siege of Yorktown .
#Text=The private Yorktown Victory Center ( admission required ) , located near the Park Service 's site , offers additional perspective and recreations of the battle .
#Text=Yorktown also offers public beach access and shopping along the York River .
#Text=Williamsburg is located approximately 30 minutes from Gloucester Point via the National Park Service 's Colonial Parkway .
#Text=Colonial Williamsburg offers a living recreation of the colonial capital of Virginia .
#Text=Located near the Colonial Williamsburg site is the campus of the College of William and Mary .
#Text=Williamsburg is also home to numerous outlet shopping centers , and the Busch Gardens Williamsburg and Water Country USA amusement parks .
#Text=Jamestown is located approximately 45 minutes from Gloucester Point .
#Text=Home to the first permanent English settlement in the U.S. , Jamestown is home to the National Park Service 's Historic Jamestowne and the state-managed Jamestown Settlement Park .
